WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
So I'm going to talk about perturbed combinations in CIL and Richter transformation today.

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:13.920
Here are my disclosures. So here's a summary of the ongoing studies involving perturbed-based

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:21.360
combinations. You can see in the relapsed CIL setting, it's either PV, PVR, PVO, doublet or

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:30.400
triplet. In the frontline setting, you have PO or PV doublet and then PVO triplet. In the setting

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:34.560
of Richter transformation, there are single-agent data and then there are a number of ongoing

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:39.760
studies using different strategies. So in the interest of time and availability of data,

00:00:39.760 --> 00:00:42.400
I'm only going to highlight a few studies here.

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:50.960
So first of all, in the relapsed CIL setting, so this is a study within the brewing trial,

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:50.960
a small CIL study. So this is a study within the brewing trial, a small CIL study. So this is a

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:50.960
study within the brewing trial, a small CIL study. So this is a study within the brewing trial,

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:50.960
a small CIL study. So this is a study within the brewing trial,

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:50.960
a small CIL study. So this is a study within the brewing trial,

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:50.960
a small CIL study. So this is a study within the brewing trial,

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:53.600
a small CIL study. So this is a study within the brewing trial, a small cohort of PV or PVR

00:00:53.600 --> 00:01:00.000
combinations by my colleague, Dr. Rooker. So this is a fixed-duration therapy, about two years.

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:05.040
Many patients got chemoimmunotherapy and two students got a PTK inhibitor already.

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:10.400
So in the table, you can see the response rate, almost 100% response. In the bottom,

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:17.120
you can see the MRD response kinetics. Despite the response, CRA is not very high,

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:20.560
but you can see with ongoing treatment, you can see deep

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:27.760
deepening MRD responses with both combinations. Now, in terms of progression and overall survival,

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:33.600
here, looking at the data, how to judge that glass half-full or half-empty. If you look at the

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:40.000
Murano trial in the setting of the PTK-naive patients, the two-year PFS and OS is above 90%,

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.680
but in PTK-exposed patients, single agent VEN, they only get you two-year PFS probably.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:50.240
So here are two sets of the patient with PTK-exposed, and you can see the two-year PFS,

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:56.120
with either PV or PVO, in my mind, appears very decent and efficacious.

00:01:57.860 --> 00:02:04.460
So based on that data, and there's an ongoing phase three trial comparing VR versus PVR.

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:09.620
So here, because Murano is in the BTK-native setting, so this trial primarily going to

00:02:09.620 --> 00:02:13.160
address the question whether Pertor adds anything on top of VR.

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:20.260
So although BTK-inhibitor exposure will be allowed, it would be capped at 20%.

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:22.220
So this trial should be reading out soon.

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:24.420
So we'll see whether PVR is better than VR.

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:30.360
And more importantly, in the BTK-exposed setting, this small cohort, does that inform

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:31.260
us anything there?

00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:37.600
Now, moving on to a front-line setting, there are different doublet and triplet ongoing

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:37.980
studies.

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:43.240
So this is a study that we are doing in Mayo, fully accrued hope to present later this year.

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:46.780
It's a MRE-guided Pertor-Venn combination.

00:02:47.020 --> 00:02:50.340
You start with Pertor debulking for three months, and then you add Venn.

00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:53.360
And everybody continues until 15 cycles.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:57.560
And then if they are MRE-negative in both peripheral blood and bone marrow, they can

00:02:57.560 --> 00:02:57.900
stop.

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:02.780
If either component is positive, you keep going for six cycles more, and then assess

00:03:02.780 --> 00:03:03.040
again.

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:07.000
In the end, the maximum treatment duration is 27 cycles.

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:10.900
So again, we'll look forward to see the data.

00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:13.820
So this is another ongoing study.

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:19.040
I was thinking, after my PV study, I can do a randomized trial, but Germans did it for

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:19.260
me.

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:22.920
So they're comparing PV versus VO.

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:24.740
With the PV, they have two strategies.

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:26.840
One is a fixed duration, 15 cycles.

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:29.220
The other is more interesting, the MRE-guided.

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:33.540
We're not going to go into the detail how they're deciding the treatment duration, but

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:34.740
this is a very important trial.

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:40.700
A PVO study by MD Anderson showed very high efficacy.

00:03:40.700 --> 00:03:44.800
So it's basically on top of a VO backbone.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.760
They add Pertor for one year.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:49.480
So it's a fixed duration therapy.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:50.360
But if the patient...

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:55.720
If the patient are MRD-positive by UMRD-5 threshold, they can continue for another year.

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:03.240
So when they presented this data first in the EHA a couple of years ago, the UMRD-4

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:04.980
rate, it was shockingly good.

00:04:05.180 --> 00:04:06.680
So this is the update from ASH.

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:08.640
The data remains very robust.

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:15.560
If you look at just UMRD-4 at the end of one year, it's almost 100%, you know, MRD negativity.

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:20.160
If you look at UMRD-6 by Clonal-Seq, still very high, 86 in the blood.

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:21.720
74 in the bone marrow.

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:23.820
I have never seen anything like that.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:27.780
Additional data who are failing their MRD.

00:04:28.180 --> 00:04:33.360
So in patients with high-risk disease, if they have either 17P deletion or T53 mutation,

00:04:33.780 --> 00:04:36.300
they actually did very well, or MRD negative.

00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:42.120
But the ones who had both 17P and T53 mutation, you have a high proportion of patients who

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:44.160
don't achieve MRD-6 at the end.

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:49.960
Most of the patients were able to stop treatment after one year because they achieved MRD.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:56.400
11 patients per particle are able to continue to the second year, and most of the patients

00:04:56.400 --> 00:04:58.800
are continuing the therapy in the second year now.

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:05.000
Moving on to Richter's, this is the single agent data where the patient received a medium

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:09.440
two prior lines of CIL therapy and two lines of Richter's therapy, yet the response was

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:12.900
50%, very good in a phase two trial.

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:15.160
And then time to progression data here.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:19.700
If you look at the numbers, it may not seem so impressive, but historically, remember,

00:05:19.760 --> 00:05:26.000
after relapse for Richter's disease, the median pre-effects in OS are very dismal.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:32.000
In fact, with some of the older data, median OS from the very beginning of Richter's is only

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:32.420
one year.

00:05:32.420 --> 00:05:35.300
So this data did look very promising at that time.

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:41.360
And they reached out to us to do a synthetic control comparison because that was a single

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:42.020
arm trial.

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:44.780
You know, any kind of comparison has its limitations.

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:49.560
But if you don't do any kind of adjustment, you're comparing apples and oranges, but if you do some

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:53.040
attempt of adjustment, at least maybe you're comparing spaghetti versus ramen.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:59.460
So here, in terms of PFS to OS, so we matched for age and prior lines of CIL and Richter's

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:00.280
treatment and LDH.

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:05.940
So PFS is slightly better than the usual treatment, which is in our group, about 80% chemo and

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:12.520
immunotherapy in older times and 20% so-called novel HSBTK, you know, PCL2 inhibitors, PD-1

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:14.100
and so on and so forth.

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:19.360
In terms of overall survival, there's a clear difference that Pertol compared.

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:21.740
They're favorable to historical controls.

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:29.800
MDSN also presented a PVO study for Richter's this year, the ASH, very similar treatment strategy.

00:06:29.800 --> 00:06:33.540
Here, the only difference is that, you know, because of Richter's, they're going to treat for two

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:34.300
years at least.

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:39.340
And in the end, if patients are still benefiting, they can continue for Pertol for another year.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:41.920
Now, this is the baseline features.

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:46.180
So colon relationship is usually very difficult to determine here.

00:06:46.180 --> 00:06:48.680
There's only three, but all three are related.

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:56.920
So 10 relapsed and five treatment-naive Richters, for the treatment-naive folks, they all had prior CRL treatment.

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:01.820
In terms of response rate, this is a very encouraging, like 80% response rate.

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:04.080
The three patients did not respond and unfortunately died.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:09.800
Now for the 12 patients who responded, their follow-up data showed us that it seems to be very durable.

00:07:10.100 --> 00:07:12.500
Three patients went to allo, two were doing good.

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:18.960
The other unfortunately died from TBHT because that was the second allo for the patient, and no one, that patient got an allo for CRL

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:19.460
before.

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:24.020
For the remaining patients, they are all responding with continued treatment.

00:07:24.020 --> 00:07:25.620
So it looks very promising.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.280
Early PFS and OS data looks very good.

00:07:28.280 --> 00:07:35.680
And again, remember, you know, for relapsed Richters or even treatment-naive Richters, his CRL data doesn't look so good.

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:41.300
So here, at one year, you're looking at an OS and PFS at 80 to 90%.

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:46.520
Certainly, we're looking forward to see prolonged follow-up and maybe more patients from this cohort.

00:07:48.760 --> 00:08:02.000
In the interest of time, I'm not going to read all through, through all these summaries, but portal-based combination seems very efficacious in both frontline and relapsed CRL, and it looks very promising in Richters, especially in combination with different interesting strategies.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:02.500
All right.

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:03.000
Thank you.
